#compdef ipx
# ============================================================================
# ipx - high-performance image optimization HTTP
#        server (TypeScript -> Node, MIT)
#
# Author : unjs (UnJS - the broader Nuxt-adjacent
#           tooling collective)
# Upstream: https://github.com/unjs/ipx
# npm    : ipx (binary: ipx)
#
# `ipx` is an HTTP image optimization microservice
# that serves on-the-fly-transformed images from
# either a filesystem source directory OR allowed
# remote HTTP(s) domains. The transformation
# pipeline is URL-driven: a request like
# `/_ipx/w_300,f_webp/photo.jpg` resizes the source
# image to 300px wide + converts to WebP, with
# response caching keyed on the transformation URL
# fragment.
#
# Architecture:
#   - HTTP server (h3-based) accepts transformation
#     requests
#   - URL fragment parser decodes transformation
#     directives (w_300 = width, f_webp = format,
#     q_80 = quality, etc.)
#   - Source storage adapters pull raw images from
#     local FS or allowed HTTP(s) hosts
#   - libvips (via lovell/sharp Node binding) performs
#     the transformation
#   - HTTP response headers carry Cache-Control +
#     ETag for downstream CDN caching
#   - SSRF protection: external URLs only accepted
#     for hosts in the --domains allowlist
#
# Used by:
#   - Nuxt Image (the official Nuxt 3 image module)
#   - Vue Img (Vue 3 image module)
#   - Many static-site generators in the unjs +
#     Nuxt + Astro + Vite ecosystem
#
# Usage:
#   ipx <command> [options]
#
# Commands:
#   serve                  - start the IPX HTTP
#                             server
#
# Serve flags (parseArgs via node:util):
#   --dir <dir>            - source directory for
#                             FS storage (env:
#                             IPX_FS_DIR, default:
#                             cwd)
#   --domains <list>       - allowed HTTP source
#                             domains, comma-
#                             separated (env:
#                             IPX_HTTP_DOMAINS)
#   --port <number>        - listen port (env: PORT,
#                             default: 3000)
#   --host <host>          - bind address (env:
#                             HOST, default:
#                             0.0.0.0)
#   -h, --help             - print help
#   -v, --version          - print version
#
# Environment:
#   IPX_FS_DIR             - filesystem source dir
#   IPX_FS_MAX_AGE         - FS source Cache-
#                             Control max-age
#                             (default 300s)
#   IPX_HTTP_DOMAINS       - allowed HTTP domains
#   IPX_HTTP_MAX_AGE       - HTTP source max-age
#                             (default 300s)
#   IPX_HTTP_FETCH_OPTIONS - extra fetch options
#                             (timeout, headers, ...)
#   PORT                   - listen port
#   HOST                   - bind address
#
# URL transformation directives (subset; full list
# in upstream docs):
#   w_<n>                  - width (px)
#   h_<n>                  - height (px)
#   q_<n>                  - quality (1-100)
#   f_<fmt>                - output format: webp /
#                             avif / png / jpeg / gif
#   fit_<mode>             - fit mode: cover /
#                             contain / fill / inside
#                             / outside
#   pos_<pos>              - position: center / top /
#                             bottom / left / right /
#                             ...
#   bg_<color>             - background color (when
#                             fit != cover)
#   blur_<n>               - Gaussian blur sigma
#   sharpen_<n>            - unsharp mask
#   rotate_<deg>           - rotate by degrees
#   flip / flop            - vertical / horizontal
#                             flip
#   grayscale / negate     - color filters
#
# Example URLs:
#   /_ipx/w_300/photo.jpg
#   /_ipx/w_300,h_200,fit_cover/photo.jpg
#   /_ipx/w_1200,f_avif,q_70/path/to/image.png
#
# The lovell/sharp lane is built on `sharp ^0.34.3`
# (declared at upstream package.json HEAD as a direct
# dep, used via the IPX transformer pipeline as
# `sharp(buffer).resize({...}).webp({...}).toBuffer()`),
# the canonical Node high-performance image
# processing library by Lovell Fuller - github.com/
# lovell/sharp, 30000+ stars on the main repo.
#
# sharp is an N-API binding to libvips - a streaming
# image-processing C library by John Cupitt at
# Kew Gardens originally + now Imperial College
# London. libvips's distinguishing feature is its
# *demand-driven streaming pixel pipeline*: instead
# of loading the entire image into memory + applying
# transformations sequentially, libvips processes
# the image as a stream of pixel chunks flowing
# through the transformation graph, requiring only
# the memory needed for the current chunk + a small
# look-ahead buffer.
#
# This means sharp can:
#   - Process huge images (gigapixel-scale) in
#     megabyte-scale memory
#   - Maintain high throughput by overlapping I/O +
#     pixel processing
#   - Avoid OOM kills on memory-constrained
#     environments (Docker containers, AWS Lambda,
#     Cloudflare Workers)
#
# Compared to alternatives:
#   - jimp (pure-JS): no native binding required;
#     ~10-30x slower; OOM on large images; cleaner
#     deployment (no node-gyp)
#   - gm (binding to GraphicsMagick CLI): subprocess-
#     based; slower per-operation but no native
#     compilation; requires gm CLI on system PATH
#   - canvas (binding to Cairo/Pango): primarily for
#     drawing; less optimized for image
#     transformation; complex deployment
#   - sharp (binding to libvips): fastest +
#     lowest-memory; N-API binding survives Node
#     major version upgrades; ~30x faster than
#     ImageMagick at common operations
#
# sharp is by far the highest-volume Node image
# library by weekly downloads (~14M weekly downloads
# of `sharp`, ~3.5M weekly downloads of
# `@img/sharp-linux-x64`, etc.), having been the
# de-facto canonical for ~10 years (since Fuller
# started it in 2013).
#
# Lovell Fuller's broader ecosystem footprint:
#   - sharp (canonical Node image)
#   - @img/sharp-* prebuilt binaries (cross-platform
#     prebuilt distributions)
#   - libvips's Node JavaScript bindings (the
#     underlying C library)
#
# ipx uses sharp throughout the transformation
# pipeline:
#   - `sharp(input).metadata()` for source-image
#     introspection
#   - `sharp(input).resize({width, height, fit, ...})`
#     for the geometry pass
#   - `sharp(input).toFormat(format, {quality, ...})`
#     for the format-conversion pass
#   - `sharp(input).rotate(deg)` + `flip()` + `flop()`
#     + `blur()` + `sharpen()` for individual
#     directive transforms
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 259 :: Image processing libraries (multi-format
#              decoders + encoders + transformation
#              primitives)
# Round 1477 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 259
#                                       (252nd axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : image-rs/image                [R1475 _wpc]
#             umbrella
#   Go      : disintegration/imaging        [R1476 _watermark-to-image]
#             (stdlib extension)
#   TS/Node : lovell/sharp                  [R1477 THIS FILE]
#             (libvips binding)
#
# lovell/sharp closes Axis 259 with the *native-
# library-binding* pattern. The three lanes form a
# clean spectrum of image-processing implementation
# strategies:
#
#   - Rust (image-rs/image): pure-Rust multi-format
#     umbrella; tree-shaking-friendly with optional
#     features per format; no FFI
#   - Go (disintegration/imaging): stdlib extension
#     adding transformation primitives on top of the
#     Go stdlib's `image/*` packages; pure-Go
#   - Node (lovell/sharp): N-API binding to libvips
#     C library; demand-driven streaming pixel
#     pipeline; ~30x faster than alternatives at
#     common operations
#
# Each lane reflects a fundamental tradeoff in its
# host ecosystem:
#   - Rust prefers pure-Rust libraries (no FFI)
#   - Go prefers pure-Go stdlib-extending libraries
#     (no FFI; cross-compile-friendly)
#   - Node accepts native bindings when they deliver
#     order-of-magnitude perf wins (sharp's libvips
#     binding is the canonical example)
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# PNG / JPEG / GIF / TIFF / WebP file decoded by
# image-rs + disintegration/imaging + lovell/sharp
# produces structurally identical pixel data
# (modulo per-decoder color management for embedded
# ICC profiles).
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - wpc (Rust, image-rs): wallpaper rotator with
#     image-rs for dimension validation + grayscale +
#     luminance extraction
#   - watermark-to-image (Go, disintegration/imaging):
#     batch PNG watermark applier
#   - ipx (Node, sharp): HTTP image optimization
#     microservice with URL-driven transformation
#     pipeline + libvips streaming
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (desktop
# wallpaper / batch watermark / HTTP optimizer),
# three implementation strategies (pure-Rust /
# stdlib-extension Go / libvips C-binding Node), all
# converging on the same image format
# specifications.
#
# Axis 259 closes the round 1477 cycle - 252nd axis
# closed total.
# ============================================================================

_ipx() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args
    local curcontext="$curcontext" ret=1

    _arguments -C \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1: :_ipx_cmds' \
        '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

    case $state in
        args)
            case $words[1] in
                serve)
                    _arguments \
                        '--dir[source directory for FS storage]:dir:_files -/' \
                        '--domains[allowed HTTP source domains (comma-separated)]:list:' \
                        '--port[listen port (default 3000)]:port:' \
                        '--host[bind address (default 0.0.0.0)]:host:' \
                        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_ipx_cmds() {
    local -a cmds
    cmds=(
        'serve:start the IPX HTTP image optimization server'
    )
    _describe -t commands 'ipx command' cmds
}

_ipx "$@"
